abstract: The pressure  has increased over the North-west and upper lakes, thence to Missouri and Kentucky, with colder weather and North-west winds. Southerly winds, warmer, cloudy, and rainy weather prevail in the Southern States. North-easterly and north-westerly winds falling barometer, cloudy and rainy weather over the lower lakes, the Middle, and Eastern States, with higher temperature, except in the latter. The rivers have risen at St. Louis, Memphis, Cincinnati, and Louisville, and fallen at Pittsburg.

abstract: The annual dinner of the Williams College Alumni Association of New-York and vicinity was given at Delmonico's last evening. Hon. William Cullen Bryant occupied the chair, supported by Rev. Dr. William Adams, Rev. C.A. Stoddard, D.D., Rev. Iren us Prime, and several of the members of the College Faculty. After the discussion of an elaborate menu, the Chairman called the meeting to order, and delivered the opening address.

abstract: Mr. Barnum was  renominated for Congress in the Fourth District today, though not with the same unanimity that has characterized the previous conventions, as out of 108 votes there were forty-six against him, all from Fairfield County. abstract: ALBANY, March 9. Stevens, the contumacious witness, was arraigned before the bar of the House to-night. The proceedings, it must be confessed, were not likely to increase his respect for the body for which he is said to have expressed contempt. abstract: The first really bold example of legislative jockeying that has come up during the present session was developed to-day in the Assembly on the passage of one of the three bills now before the Legislature designed to transfer the process patronage of the Marine Court to Sheriff Conner. abstract: ALBANY, N. Y. March 16. The General Savings Bank bill, as framed in and reported from the Committee on Banks, was under consideration in Committee of the Whole in the Assembly to-night. An amendment offered by Mr. Alvord, providing that no salaried officer of any savings bank shall be a trustee thereof, was adopted. The committee finally progressed the bill, and it was made the special order of business for Thursday evening.

abstract: The memory of Ireland's patron saint was duly commemorated throughout the State of NewJersey yesterday by parades of societies and organizations. The parade in Jersey City was the largest and finest ever seen there. The line was formed on Jersey avenue, with the right resting on Newark avenue. At 10 o'clock the various societies arrived at this point, and at 11:30 the line was formed and the march up Jersey avenue to Hamilton Park begun.

abstract: LONDON, March 18. The Liverpool Spring meeting, commenced on Tuesday, was continued yesterday and to-day, and closes tomorrow, thus giving four days racing, under the Newmarket and Grand National rules. The most notable event of the meeting is the Grand National steeplechase, which took place to-day, and for which nineteen started, out of eighty-six subscribers, twenty-two of whom declared out, and each paid five sovereigns forfeit.

abstract: According to a "military communication" in the Cologne Gazette, the Russian forces in Asia, if the Russo-Asiatic forces be alone taken into consideration, are not proportionate to the tremendous task undertaken there by Russia. The troops immediately ready for active employment number together 60,800 men, with 32,650 horses and 112 cannons. Of reserves destined to take the field may be added a total of 25,750 men, and 9.650 horses.

The latest dispatches from up and down the river report clear water from Selin's Grove, near Sunbury, and fifty miles above Harrisburg to Columbia, which is twenty-eight miles below this place.

abstract: I saw last year ano  other splendid and distinctive sight, which lives vividly in my mountaineer's memory. I mean a solitary piece of rock-climbing by Melchior Anderegg, which for danger and difficulty, for courage and skill, has scarcely, I should think, ever been equaled, has certainly never been surpassed, by man. We started to cross from the Montanvert to Courmayeur by the newly-discovered Col des Hirondelles.

abstract: ROCHESTER, N.Y., March 29.--The Rochester Ring feel very insecure to-night, and wonder much What new part of their machinations THE TIMES will get hold of. The Lords are silent but active, and have set their emissaries to work in every part of the State wherein they have operated to cover up or erase their tracks.
